# Error Codes, Context, and Suggestions: When Error Messages Teach

@meta {
  title: "Error Codes, Context, and Suggestions: When Error Messages Teach"
  date: "2026-04-03"
  author: "bad-antics"
  tags: ["error messages", "documentation", "context"]
  reading_time: "5 min"
}

@heading level=1 {
  Error Codes, Context, and Suggestions: When Error Messages Teach
}

@paragraph {
  Error messages are an essential part of the developer experience. But what happens when you're stuck on a tricky problem and the error message doesn't help? In this post we explore how to turn error messages into a valuable resource for debugging.
}

@code lang=lateralus {
  fn get_error_message() {
    return {error_code} with {context}
  }
  let error = get_error_message()
  error |> debug()

  # Example
  fn example(param: string) -> string {
      if param == "" {
          return "Please enter something."
      } else {
          return param
      }
  }

  fn main() {
      let answer = example(" ")
      answer |> print()
  }
}

@paragraph { ... }

@heading level=2 {
  The Power of Context
}

@paragraph {
  When we think about it, error messages should be more than just a cryptic number or generic text. They should provide context — information that helps us understand why an error occurred and how to fix it. This isn't always possible, but when it is, the results can be incredibly powerful.
}

@paragraph { ... }

@heading level=3 {
  How LATERALUS Helps
}

@paragraph {
  At LATERALUS, we've always believed that the best code is not just written by humans, but also reviewed by them. We use our own internal tools to help catch errors early in development. But sometimes these tools don't work as intended. That's where LATERALUS comes in — our comprehensive documentation provides valuable context for debugging and learning.
}

@paragraph { ... }

@heading level=4 {
  Best Practices
}

@paragraph {
  Here are some guidelines for writing effective error messages:
  - Provide context: give users enough information about what went wrong so they can diagnose the issue quickly.
  - Avoid cryptic numbers: instead of a generic "error 1", explain why it occurred and how to fix it.
  - Be specific: if possible, include examples or sample inputs that led to the error.

  # Example
  fn example(param: int) -> string {
      return param |> format()
  }
}

@code lang=lateralus {
  fn format() {
      return str(format_string("Hello, {}!", param))
  }
}
</script>
